@ancestors ["Krowne, A. P. (2003). An Architecture for Collaborative Math and Science Digital Libraries. Virginia Tech MS thesis.  (sustainability triangle)" "UKRN WP §4 / draft-16-april §4 (triangle-to-tetrahedron; bootstrap sequence; openness/governance Pareto table; explicit Tension/Composition/Check)" "UKRN role-codebook analysis (4/4 transcripts show EV_analyse absent; evidence apex absent across Cycle 0)" "ORP evaluation ethics approval (King's College London, MRA-23/24-42968) — the existing governance surface on which low-cost deposits can run" "equity/visible-impact (diagnoses the feedback failure this pattern answers)" "equity/shared-maintenance (diagnoses the upstreaming failure this pattern partly answers)" "Ostrom (1990) commons governance principles"]

! conclusion: A distributed training service does not become a learning system just because good work happens locally.  Local success has to become shareable evidence: something that other institutions, partners, and funders can inspect, reuse, or act on.  Every service event therefore sits on an axis between shareability gain and governance cost.  The service should be explicit about what is worth sharing, what it costs to share it responsibly, and when the extra governance burden is justified.

  + context: The current paper's background and synthesis point to the same problem from two directions.  First, the three lines of evidence — training delivery, what can currently be measured, and sector priorities — are often not joined up.  Second, funder and policy cycles matter to whether local work becomes visible beyond the institution that did it.  A service that leaves training outcomes, evaluation findings, and operational learning trapped locally will keep recreating the same work in parallel and will struggle to build wider recognition for what it does.

  + IF:
    The pattern operates on the axis: shareability gain ↔ governance cost.
    Irreducible: making evidence portable, reusable, and externally legible usually requires extra governance work.  Avoiding that work keeps things easy locally, but it also keeps the learning trapped.

  + HOWEVER:
    Real costs: some things are cheap to share, such as a training plan, a scaffold, or a summary of what was tried.  Other things, such as downstream evaluation, cross-institution comparison, or evidence that could affect institutional reputation, require much more consent, handling, and trust.
    Active dynamic: the governance cost of sharing should fall as the network builds routine practice, trusted formats, and repeatable agreements.  But it never falls to zero, and the service still has to choose where the higher-cost sharing really pays.

    + FAILURE-MODES:
      - Local-success trap: good work happens, but no one outside the host institution can learn from it
      - Governance-free sharing: evidence is pushed outward without the consent, attribution, or handling needed to do it responsibly
      - Governance-without-reuse: governance effort is paid, but the resulting evidence is too thin or too obscure to matter
      - Post-dependent memory: the shared layer depends on a specific funded role and disappears when that role ends
      - Sector disconnect: the service shares internally but never in forms that connect to funder or partner conversations
      - Archive-without-consequence: evidence is technically deposited, but nothing downstream uses it

  + THEN: Choose what to make shareable, and cost the governance honestly.
    + COMPOSITIONS:
      (1) Low-governance shared layer: make planning materials, role definitions, routine findings, and annual scenario outputs shareable first, while holding back heavier cross-institution evidence until the governance surface is ready.  Gives up some comparative power.
      (2) Governance-first build-out: invest early in the agreements and processes needed for higher-value cross-institution evidence sharing.  Gives up speed.
      (3) Subset sharing: build the fuller shared layer with a smaller group of institutions willing to carry the burden first, and let the rest of the network inherit what is learned from that arrangement.  Gives up uniformity.
      These compositions are not ranked in the abstract.  The right one depends on what evidence the service most needs to move from local usefulness to network usefulness.

    + CHECK:
      Engaged when: the service can say what each event leaves behind for the network; the governance burden of sharing is named rather than assumed away; and the shared layer persists beyond the immediate funding cycle or project team.
      Failing when: every institution has to rediscover the same things for itself; governance work is performed ceremonially; or the shared artefacts disappear with the post or grant that created them.

  + BECAUSE:
    Network learning requires a shared layer: The paper's central move is from isolated training activity toward a coordinated learning system.  That move fails if evidence never leaves the place where it was produced.

    Wider recognition depends on shareable evidence: Funders and policy actors cannot act on local success they cannot see.  A service that wants sector-level standing needs forms of evidence that travel beyond the originating institution.

    Persistence matters as much as publication: A one-off shared output is not yet infrastructure.  The pattern is about creating deposits that later cycles can inherit, revise, and build on.

    Governance is part of the work, not an afterthought: The question is not whether evidence should be shared in the abstract, but which evidence is worth sharing at which governance cost.  Making that trade explicit is what keeps the pattern from becoming either secrecy by default or openness as a slogan.

    Mechanic, in short:
    Derived from the paper's need to connect local delivery, usable evidence, and sector recognition into one operating story.
    Answers the service-level version of the visible-impact and shared-maintenance problems: what one institution learns should become part of the network's usable memory.
    Mapped to the learning loop at the deposit step: evidence produced locally enters a shared layer so later actors can build on it.
    Coordination requirement: Low for routine artefacts, high for cross-institution evaluation and anything carrying reputational consequence.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - Decide, for each class of event, what the network-level deposit is meant to be
    - State the governance cost of that deposit before treating it as routine
    - Prefer deposits that can survive role turnover and funding-cycle turnover
    - Make at least some outputs legible not only internally but to funders, partners, and incoming member institutions
    - Use this pattern alongside measurement selection and design revision, so shared evidence is both chosen deliberately and acted on
